This is my portfolio piece dedicated to Joey. I figure, whats more romantic than writing a code for someone? To do this project, I asked him to give me any question hes interested in. He settled on whos the best rapper?. For this project I will be using two datasets. The first dataset tells me the diversity of vocabularies for each rapper. The second dataset gives me information about about the popularity of hip hop artists. Ill be looking at lyrical complexity and popularity as indicators of being the best rapper (which is probably wrong, but I dont really know if there even is a quantitative method to determine the best rapper).

  filter(ambiguous_artist == FALSE)

Theres also some missing data in the lyrics data. Lets get rid of that.

all_data <- all_data %>%
  filter(words != "Not enough" & words != "not enough" & nzchar(words) == TRUE)

Busdriver has the most complex lyrics with 7,324 words. Lil baby has the least complex lyrics with 2,762 words. Lets look at the box plot of words by era and the descriptives. As part of the box plot code, Ive removed commas from the data: R didnt like that when converting it to numeric. Also, were going to make the graph Ninja Turtle colored for Joey.

all_data[,'words'] <- gsub(",","",all_data[,'words'])
all_data %>%
   ggplot(aes(x=era, y= as.numeric(words), fill=era)) +
   geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous("Number of words used", breaks = c(1000, 2000, 3000, 4000, 5000, 6000, 7000, 8000), labels = c("1000", "2000", "3000", "4000", "5000", "6000", "7000", "8000")) +
  scale_x_discrete(name ="Era", 
                    limits=c("1980s", "1990s", 
                             "2000s", "2010s")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("red", "#56B4E9", "orange", "purple")) + 
  labs(title = "Number of words used by era")
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (stat_boxplot).

The minimum number of words is least during the 2010s, and the maximum number of words is greatest during the 2000s. Lil baby is from the 2010s and Busdriver is from the 2000s, so this makes sense. The median from the 1980s to the 2000s stayed pretty constant (between 4500 and 5000), but it plummeted in the 2010s (between 3500 and 4000). The interquartile range is greatest for the 2000s (but seemingly not that much greater than the 1990s and the 2010s), and smallest for the 1980s. I think the main take-away from this graph is that hip hop became much less complex during the 2010s. Lets look at descriptives to see if thats supported.

As we saw in the graph, the 2010s have the lowest minimum and the 2000s have the highest maximum. The 1980s and the 2000s have similar means. The 2000s have the highest mean and the 2010s have the lowest mean. So, if youre interested in rappers with complex vocabularies, you should probably listen to something from the 2000s. If you want something simple, then the 2010s is the way to go.

To conclude this section, if having a complex vocabulary is equated with being the best rapper, then Busdriver is the best rapper. He is also from the era of the most complex lyrics, so maybe the 2000s are also the best era for hip hop. The 2000s have the highest maximum and the 1980s have the lowest minimum. The 2000s also have the highest mean and the 2010s have the lowest mean. So, generally people listen to hip hop from the 2000s more than they listen to hip hop from the 2010s. This is interesting because we also saw that the 2000s had the highest mean lyrical complexity, while the 2010s had the lowest mean lyrical complexity. Do people enjoy listening to greater lyrical complexity? Thats a question for another time. Now, we turn to comparing popularity and lyrical complexity.

Were going to make a scatter plot with number of words on the x-axis and number of listens on the y-axis with an era fill.

all_data <- all_data %>%
  filter(nzchar(era) == TRUE & era != "1999s")
all_data %>%
   ggplot(aes(x=as.numeric(words), y= listeners_lastfm, color = era)) +
   geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous("Listeners on lastfm", breaks = c(500000, 1000000, 1500000, 2000000, 2500000, 3000000, 3500000, 4000000, 4500000, 5000000), labels = c("500000", "1000000", "1500000", "2000000", "2500000", "3000000", "3500000", "4000000", "4500000", "5000000")) +

  scale_color_manual(values=c("red", "#56B4E9", "orange", "purple")) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, aes(group = 1), color="black") +
  labs(title = "Listeners on lastfm versus lyrical complexity")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Well, this is a depressing plot: as lyrical complexity increases, popularity decreases. This goes against the hypothesis I had in the previous section that the reason that people listen to 2000s hip hop more is because of lyrical complexity. Finally, some good news! For artists with high lyrical complexity, the higher the lyrical complexity, the greater the popularity.

Okay, what have we learned: Busdriver has the greatest lyrical complexity which puts him in the running for being the best rapper. Alternatively, Eminem is the most popular MC which also puts him in the running for being the best rapper. For most rappers, lyrical complexity is negatively correlated with popularity. This relationship does not hold for the artists with the highest lyrical complexity. Here, lyrical complexity is associated more popularity. If you want to be the best rapper, but youre not great with words, thats fine: you can still be super popular. If you want to be the best rapper, and youre one of the best with words, youll also be popular. Im leaning towards Busdriver as the best rapper because hes the most popular among the great lyricists.
